  "answer": "**The Falsafa corpus does not contain direct discussions by Allama Iqbal (or any other author) on the concepts of *'aql* (reason or intellect) and *ishq* (passionate love), nor their relationship.**\n\nIqbal's works in the corpus are limited to the three parts of his Urdu poetry collection *Bang-e-Dara* (1924), which focus on themes like Islamic renaissance, self-realization, nationalism, and spiritual awakening.[^1][^2][^3] Searches across the English translations of these texts for terms like \"aql\", \"ishq\", \"reason\", \"intellect\", and \"love\" (in connection with Iqbal) yielded no results. While Iqbal extensively explores *'aql* and *ishq* in his Persian works (e.g., *Asrar-e-Khudi*) and English prose (e.g., *The Reconstruction of Religious Thought in Islam*)—often portraying *ishq* as a dynamic force transcending the limits of *'aql*—these texts are not part of the current 37-work corpus.\n\nIf future additions include Iqbal's prose or Persian poetry, this topic could be addressed from primary sources here.\n\n[^1]: *Allama Iqbal, Bang-E-Dara Part 1* (metadata via `list_works`).\n[^2]: *Allama Iqbal, Bang-E-Dara Part 2* (metadata via `list_works`).\n[^3]: *Allama Iqbal, Bang-E-Dara Part 3* (metadata via `list_works`).",
